Apply bayesian Graphical Models to multi-omics data

Johann Hawe

In this script we will load individual datasets and apply the bayesian GGM algorithm implemented in the BDgraph package to them, using priors for the individual links possible in the underlying graph structure. Priors have to be created beforehand and provided as RData files on the results folder.

After preparing all needed libraries and methods, we now load the data we want to use in the BDgraph algorithm.

# load data into new environment
env <- new.env()
load("data/lolipop/rs9859077.data.RData", envir=env)
ggm.data <- with(env, sentinel)
id <- with(env, id)
data.matrix <- ggm.data$data
ranges <- ggm.data
ranges$data <- NULL
nodes <- colnames(data.matrix)
head(data.matrix)

Loaded data matrix dimension is 612, 132. Now we get the priors for all possible links within the data matrix. The priors need to have been created beforehand and are simply loaded in the called function.

Loading string db.
Using results/string.validated.RData as cache file.
Loading previously saved network.
Done.
Prior min-value:  1e-07

In the next step we finally fit the GGM to our data, using the priors during the process. First a ‘start-graph’ is created, which serves as the entry point in the calculations for the algorithms.

Heatmap of the start graph (of incidence matrix):

Now we can start running the bdgraph algorithm in order to get our partial correlations based on data and prior knowledge.

iter=50000
burnin=5000
cores=8

We use 510^{4} iterations with a burnin of 5000 as well as a total of 8 cores. We then extract the graph from the ggm fit and create a dot file representing the graph. If the graph is less then 500 edges it will be plotted graphically as well. In addition, we create some diagnostic plots to check the convergence of the algorithm.

ggm.fit <- bdgraph(data.matrix, 
        method="gcgm", 
        iter=iter, 
        burnin=burnin,
        save.all=T, g.start = g.start, 
        g.prior = priors, cores=10)
